## Task 3: Make Escape cancel build placement while preserving modal precedence

### rollout_summary_files

- rollout_summaries/2026-04-19T16-12-51-MKBz-idle_life_spec_to_civ_engine_plan_with_escape_cancel_refacto.md (cwd=C:\Users\38909\Documents\github\idle-life, rollout_path=C:\Users\38909\.codex\sessions\2026\04\19\rollout-2026-04-19T09-12-51-019da684-23c5-7921-bf0d-df78fd76e441.jsonl, updated_at=2026-04-20T16:43:26+00:00, thread_id=019da684-23c5-7921-bf0d-df78fd76e441, success)

### keywords

- Escape key, placement mode, confirmDialog.isOpen, dismiss, shell.ts, tabIndex = -1, placement-mode.ts, placement-mode-controller.ts, modal precedence, shell-scoped keyboard handling, app.test.ts, shell.test.ts

## User preferences

- when starting a new design effort, the user asked "Interview me on the spec of this game and summarize into a final doc" -> interview first, then synthesize a concrete doc instead of drafting from assumptions [Task 1]
- when documenting inspiration, the user said they wanted a game like the reference title but "do not mention its name in the doc" -> capture the mechanics without naming the inspiration in the deliverable [Task 1]
- when scoping milestone 1, the user said "So far let's just focus on recreating the game first" -> default the first milestone to faithful recreation before novelty [Task 1]
- when the user asked to "Turn it into an implementation plan using the game engine `civ-engine` available under `documents/github/civ-engine`. Study its docs." -> make plans engine-aware, not just feature-wishlist driven [Task 2]
- for transient UI state, the final accepted direction was shell-scoped and modal-first rather than HUD-owned -> keep transient input ownership out of the HUD when similar UI work returns [Task 3]

## Reusable knowledge

- milestone 1 was explicitly scoped to: one resident, desktop companion window, autonomous side-view traversal, mouse-only management, no jumping, no day/night cycle, no offline progress, no relationships, and real-time-only simulation [Task 1]
- the starter careers and basic house/build loop constraints were locked: Writer, Artist, Programmer; indoor-only freeform placement; all needs important but non-fatal; hunger-first; sell returns half price [Task 1]
- `civ-engine` docs show the engine is deterministic, headless, ECS-based, command/event driven, and grid-based, so "freeform" should be interpreted as fine-grid placement in simulation with smooth rendering handled separately [Task 2]
- the chosen runtime shape was worker-hosted `World`, renderer/UI on the main thread, commands/events/diffs between them, and headless scenario/debug verification via `WorldDebugger` / `runScenario()` [Task 2]
- behavior trees are a good fit for resident autonomy because they are shared-blueprint, per-entity-state, and serializable [Task 2]
- shell-level `Escape` handling should prioritize the confirm dialog, then placement cancellation; `confirmDialog.isOpen()` and `dismiss()` make that precedence explicit [Task 3]
- a focusable shell root (`tabIndex = -1`) plus focus-on-primary-pointer interaction makes shell-scoped keyboard handling reliable [Task 3]
- `placementMode` should be a small data type plus controller in `src/client/placement-mode.ts` and `src/client/placement-mode-controller.ts`, not state buried inside the HUD module [Task 3]

## Failures and how to do differently

- symptom: repo instructions mention docs/devlog/lessons files that do not exist yet -> cause: greenfield repo state -> fix: initialize the minimal docs (`docs/devlog/summary.md`, dated detailed devlog, `docs/learning/lessons.md`) before continuing deeper planning work [Task 1]
- symptom: a civ-engine-based plan assumes pixel-perfect free placement or continuous physics -> cause: planning from the fantasy instead of the engine contract -> fix: keep one authoritative integer-grid simulation and let the renderer/client shell handle smooth presentation and desktop-companion window behavior [Task 2]
- symptom: `Escape` behavior works inconsistently or fights modal dialogs -> cause: global listener arbitration and unclear ownership of transient UI state -> fix: route shortcuts through the shell boundary, make modal precedence explicit in `app.ts`, and keep the HUD out of the authority path [Task 3]

